	<item>
		<title>By: Bo Maryniuk</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/ask-scott/ask-scott-episode-5-bass-amps-warming-teaching-much.html#comment-15699</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Bo Maryniuk]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 14 Jan 2015 14:44:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=9035#comment-15699</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Scott, JFYI: MarkBass combos essentially amp + speaker, packed. So you always can either daisy-chain it with another speaker or disconnect internal and connect to external speakers as is. Myself I own one cab with 300W at 8 Ohm with 12&quot; and horn inside, which can go 500W at 4 Ohm. So if you connect either MarkBass Traveller speaker or any other from their brand to get 4 Ohm, then you get 500W and it will really blow away and you should be careful! For example, I was using 30 Hz at low B to massage listener&#039;s guts. These frequencies are also moving chairs in the big hall for 500 people and folks on the stage asked me why the cab is causing earthquakes. :-)]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Scott, JFYI: MarkBass combos essentially amp + speaker, packed. So you always can either daisy-chain it with another speaker or disconnect internal and connect to external speakers as is. Myself I own one cab with 300W at 8 Ohm with 12&#8243; and horn inside, which can go 500W at 4 Ohm. So if you connect either MarkBass Traveller speaker or any other from their brand to get 4 Ohm, then you get 500W and it will really blow away and you should be careful! For example, I was using 30 Hz at low B to massage listener&#8217;s guts. These frequencies are also moving chairs in the big hall for 500 people and folks on the stage asked me why the cab is causing earthquakes. :-)</p>
]]></content:encoded>
